<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
European Portuguese (pt-PT) translation — full UI coverage. Tu-form
throughout (2nd-person singular imperatives "Toca", "Define", "Veste",
"Leva"), the casual / intimate register the app already uses
elsewhere. No você-form: in Portugal "você" reads as semi-formal
(roughly between BR's você and "o senhor"); modern PT app UX defaults
to tu unless the brand explicitly wants distance, which we don't.
Brand name "ClothesCast" stays verbatim.

What is NOT overridden, by design:
- `app_name` — brand identifier, identical across locales.
- `insight_time_am` / `_pm` / `_midnight` / `_noon` (and *_minutes
  variants) — English-only spoken-time formatter helpers. PT
  Portuguese uses `insight_time_hour` / `_hour_minutes` ("15h" /
  "15h30") which are translated below; the AM/PM keys exist for the
  `Locale.language == "en"` path only and would never be read in a
  pt-PT runtime.

Vocabulary that diverges from pt-BR throughout this file:
- "Definições" (PT) for "Configurações" (BR)
- "Telemóvel" (PT) for "celular" / "telefone" (BR)
- "Ecrã" (PT) for "tela" (BR)
- "Dispositivo" (PT) for "aparelho" (BR) where it appears
- "Eliminar" (PT) for "Excluir" (BR)
- "Guardar" (PT) for "Salvar" (BR)
- "Partilhar" (PT) for "Compartilhar" (BR)
- "Encriptada" (PT) for "criptografada" (BR)
- "Saltar" (PT) for "Pular" (BR)
- "Obter" (PT) for "Buscar" (BR) in the "fetch now" action
- Garments: "Camisola" / "Casaco" / "T-shirt" / "Calções" / "Calças
  de ganga" — see the garment block for the full pt-BR ↔ pt-PT map.
- Insight bands / conditions: "Chuvisco" (PT) for "Garoa" (BR);
  "Trovoada" (PT) for "Tempestade" (BR).

Picker labels under `settings_region_language_*` and
`settings_tts_voice_locale_*` give the European-Portuguese names for
every offered locale (Inglês (Estados Unidos), Francês (Canadá),
Chinês (simplificado), …). The locale tag stored on disk (en-US /
fr-CA / zh-CN) is unchanged; only the displayed label localizes.
Polaco / Neerlandês / Japonês / etc. follow PT-PT conventions where
they diverge from BR ("Polonês" → "Polaco", "Holandês" →
"Neerlandês").
-->
